Authentication VS Authorization

<span key="60e4279305b94448baf0551cf44ee137"><span offset-key="60e4279305b94448baf0551cf44ee137:0">What's the difference between authentication and authorization? </span>**Authentication**<span offset-key="60e4279305b94448baf0551cf44ee137:2"> confirms that users are who they say they are. </span>**Authorization**<span offset-key="60e4279305b94448baf0551cf44ee137:4"> gives those users permission to access a resource.</span></span>

<span key="45258cd49a8449bdaabad293e46dacd9"><span offset-key="45258cd49a8449bdaabad293e46dacd9:0">While authentication and authorization might sound similar, they are distinct security processes in the world of identity and access management (IAM).</span></span>

## 

<span key="0123d6a610134aa88755be32823d00f7"><span offset-key="0123d6a610134aa88755be32823d00f7:0">What Is Authentication?</span></span>

<span key="a42c871e0ff6450f8e9aa5b481c72db1"><span offset-key="a42c871e0ff6450f8e9aa5b481c72db1:0">Authentication is the act of validating that users are whom they claim to be. This is the first step in any security process. </span></span>

<span key="2d4a8b17f27346a8a5cfcdea38edb2db"><span offset-key="2d4a8b17f27346a8a5cfcdea38edb2db:0">Complete an authentication process with:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="7301769ab3034e9d98f422a01dfa3ac4">**Passwords.** <span offset-key="7301769ab3034e9d98f422a01dfa3ac4:1">Usernames and passwords</span> <span offset-key="7301769ab3034e9d98f422a01dfa3ac4:3">are the most common </span></span><a href="https://www.okta.com/products/adaptive-multi-factor-authentication/" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="1486551b7276467aa7b9de30bb8ba721" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-57793_259-57794-237__"><span data-key="fb93c4fd6fd44f7683a7bb301783ab03"><span data-offset-key="fb93c4fd6fd44f7683a7bb301783ab03:0">authentication factors</span></span></span></a><span key="47f3073fd02a43e7a3a14419e76acbcb"><span offset-key="47f3073fd02a43e7a3a14419e76acbcb:0">. If a user enters the correct data, the system assumes the identity is valid and grants access.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="9218a9e804cc4e8298409beb7f8cd13f"><span offset-key="9218a9e804cc4e8298409beb7f8cd13f:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span><a href="https://www.okta.com/blog/2020/06/what-is-a-one-time-password-otp/" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="b39d1942a5de47d38176441c58379c89" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-57793_259-57794-237__"><span data-key="66a2f19f4e954fc4ac8cdb31543f5962"><strong>One-time pins</strong></span></span></a><span key="2e9f5b6fa7854ff8b3c4c4eb456449e9">**.**<span offset-key="2e9f5b6fa7854ff8b3c4c4eb456449e9:1"> Grant access for only one session or transaction.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="0d99941ca38b45efb32fcebb3c872f89">**Authentication apps.** <span offset-key="0d99941ca38b45efb32fcebb3c872f89:1">Generate security codes via an outside party that grants access.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="027af2ce16fa4920bb16925532809698"><span offset-key="027af2ce16fa4920bb16925532809698:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span><a href="https://www.okta.com/blog/2020/07/biometric-authentication/" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="a683d7d1affd4650b957cc0f64ca92bd" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-57793_259-57794-237__"><span data-key="5f8b5b98c7e04cffbfdf01532edf3482"><strong>Biometrics</strong></span></span></a><span key="c0539cb66cf9404a8ae8c6dc29c085e8">**.** <span offset-key="c0539cb66cf9404a8ae8c6dc29c085e8:1">A user presents a fingerprint or eye scan to gain access to the system. </span></span>

<span key="abc5f3b0804a4fff85f3f739ffbd9b85"><span offset-key="abc5f3b0804a4fff85f3f739ffbd9b85:0">In some instances, systems require the successful verification of more than one factor before granting access. This multi-factor authentication (MFA) requirement is often deployed to increase security beyond what passwords alone can provide.</span></span>

## 

<span key="13f31310d00c4388b2719c8f6035dd98"><span offset-key="13f31310d00c4388b2719c8f6035dd98:0">What Is Authorization?</span></span>

<span key="b9cadfe5389c41629541cba17bbe16f0"><span offset-key="b9cadfe5389c41629541cba17bbe16f0:0">Authorization in system security is the process of giving the user permission to access a specific resource or function. This term is often used interchangeably with access control or client privilege.</span></span>

<span key="c38315037a444a8a9935420edb90d012"><span offset-key="c38315037a444a8a9935420edb90d012:0">Giving someone permission to download a particular file on a server or providing individual users with administrative access to an application are good examples of authorization.</span></span>

<span key="d5c043db0993480ba2cb39d20be0b4d4"><span offset-key="d5c043db0993480ba2cb39d20be0b4d4:0">In secure environments, authorization must always follow authentication. Users should first prove that their identities are genuine before an organizationâ€™s administrators grant them access to the requested resources.</span></span>

<span key="f15f25dae63a406c8285f0dd9cda1c6f"><span offset-key="f15f25dae63a406c8285f0dd9cda1c6f:0">Authentication vs Authorization</span></span>

<span key="78a27b1dcaa448cab9ea2527715f2559"><span offset-key="78a27b1dcaa448cab9ea2527715f2559:0"> </span></span>

## 

<span key="0d4025cc82a946f09b9a7a90a8edfe4b"><span offset-key="0d4025cc82a946f09b9a7a90a8edfe4b:0">Authentication vs. Authorization</span></span>

<span key="1d79af61163d40ef978c6408a0d8cee3"><span offset-key="1d79af61163d40ef978c6408a0d8cee3:0">Despite the similar-sounding terms, authentication and authorization are separate steps in the login process. Understanding the difference between the two is key to successfully implementing an IAM solution.</span></span>

<span key="ab467949fdc540848b6ff79b2cebde6f"><span offset-key="ab467949fdc540848b6ff79b2cebde6f:0">Let's use an analogy to outline the differences.</span></span>

<span key="8d96a41a7603409698e8126ddf9f72bd"><span offset-key="8d96a41a7603409698e8126ddf9f72bd:0">Consider a person walking up to a locked door to provide care to a pet while the family is away on vacation. That person needs:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="fb61882d10a64843a25b65d36605b424">**Authentication**<span offset-key="fb61882d10a64843a25b65d36605b424:1">, in the form of a key. The lock on the door only grants access to someone with the correct key in much the same way that a system only grants access to users who have the correct credentials.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="955c92fc52ad498b84f851126e8eea73">**Authorization,** <span offset-key="955c92fc52ad498b84f851126e8eea73:1">in the form of permissions. Once inside, the person has the authorization to access the kitchen and open the cupboard that holds the pet food. The person may not have permission to go into the bedroom for a quick nap. </span></span>

<span key="7f3ae6c300b849a6956d928650a98aaf"><span offset-key="7f3ae6c300b849a6956d928650a98aaf:0">Authentication and authorization work together in this example. A pet sitter has the right to enter the house (authentication), and once there, they have access to certain areas (authorization).</span></span>

<span key="da9c39651d474f0f8ccaaad69b115d81"><span offset-key="da9c39651d474f0f8ccaaad69b115d81:0"> </span></span>

<span key="e0c1ac8b94564ac78ec867519e947f9d">**Authentication**</span>

<span key="a7813baab079418eacaf767dbf5255cb">**Authorization**</span>

<span key="fcd1c2a3b75d411dad2d71071fca0180">**What does it do?**</span>

<span key="a3625fa57162451aaa40d11ce03c6a6a"><span offset-key="a3625fa57162451aaa40d11ce03c6a6a:0">Verifies credentials </span></span>

<span key="97c5d32b329a4e57a61f46d57d79e9b4"><span offset-key="97c5d32b329a4e57a61f46d57d79e9b4:0">Grants or denies permissions</span></span>

<span key="f2101f557a584cddb80dac77dcf7007d">**How does it work?**</span>

<span key="3b9a487de1444fd3b3fc6aabcb52d0ac"><span offset-key="3b9a487de1444fd3b3fc6aabcb52d0ac:0">Through passwords, biometrics, one-time pins, or apps</span></span>

<span key="84c13d6847b449ef921e10516c81a47f"><span offset-key="84c13d6847b449ef921e10516c81a47f:0">Through settings maintained by security teams</span></span>

<span key="b3a3b2661b094c16874af5a665d1b1e3">**Is it visible to the user?**</span>

<span key="15dac22ccaab44b39d8875766ca6860d"><span offset-key="15dac22ccaab44b39d8875766ca6860d:0">Yes</span></span>

<span key="354ee219aef747aea6ae7348d67cde4e"><span offset-key="354ee219aef747aea6ae7348d67cde4e:0">No</span></span>

<span key="326de0d7be2c4f928b65b8e5268f6706">**It is changeable by the user?**</span>

<span key="ff01b3378a954863b591ba209128b812"><span offset-key="ff01b3378a954863b591ba209128b812:0">Partially</span></span>

<span key="b9f176b6a26d4176bd90124f2999db75"><span offset-key="b9f176b6a26d4176bd90124f2999db75:0">No </span></span>

<span key="9430eb7f449840a08da5895f5d659197">**How does data move?**</span>

<span key="90266ea7a17c4a649a0c5a117c870f3a"><span offset-key="90266ea7a17c4a649a0c5a117c870f3a:0">Through ID tokens</span></span>

<span key="a242d21ef41d45cc86aefcf14438e363"><span offset-key="a242d21ef41d45cc86aefcf14438e363:0">Through access tokens </span></span>

<span key="bbaa2ec30ca1429ba30f95f06a1ca327"><span offset-key="bbaa2ec30ca1429ba30f95f06a1ca327:0"> </span></span>

<span key="a4809f95857f479b9a869ddf031978d4"><span offset-key="a4809f95857f479b9a869ddf031978d4:0">Systems implement these concepts in the same way, so itâ€™s crucial that IAM administrators understand how to utilize both:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="bd8bf05b3cbe4764bd49a4935443764e">**Authentication.** <span offset-key="bd8bf05b3cbe4764bd49a4935443764e:1">Let every staff member access your workplace systems if they provide the right credentials in response to your chosen authentication requirements.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="b270b30ce9d547068135b635b36b54d5">**Authorization.** <span offset-key="b270b30ce9d547068135b635b36b54d5:1">Grant permission to department-specific files, and reserve access to confidential data, such as financial information, as needed. Ensure that employees have access to the files they need to do their jobs. </span></span>

<span key="2abb6a76b52c4c4482018ab80587711f"><span offset-key="2abb6a76b52c4c4482018ab80587711f:0">Understand the difference between authentication and authorization, and implement IAM solutions that have strong support for both. You will protect your organization against data breaches and enable your workforce to be more productive.</span></span>
